GRAMMAR_LESSONS = [
    {
        "id": "lesson_1",
        "title": "Parts of Speech",
        "intro": "The building blocks of English sentences.",
        "content": "Every word in a sentence serves a grammatical purpose. There are **eight basic parts of speech** that build every English sentence:\n\n### 1. Noun (Naming Word)\nA noun names a person, place, thing, or idea.\n• **Types**: Common nouns (general names like *city*, *dog*) and Proper nouns (specific names that are always capitalized, like *London*, *Bujji*).\n• **Examples**:\n  - *Bujji* is a smart robot. (Proper noun referring to a specific character)\n  - The *student* walked to *college* with *happiness*. (Common nouns referring to a person, place, and an abstract feeling)\n\n### 2. Pronoun (Noun Replacer)\nA pronoun replaces a noun to avoid repeating the same noun over and over.\n• **Types**: Personal (*I*, *you*, *he*, *she*, *it*, *they*), Possessive (*mine*, *yours*, *his*, *hers*), and Demonstrative (*this*, *that*).\n• **Examples**:\n  - Bujji said *he* would help *us* study. (*he* replaces Bujji; *us* replaces the students)\n  - *She* likes the book; *it* is very interesting. (*She* replaces a girl's name; *it* replaces the book)\n\n### 3. Verb (Action or State Word)\nA verb expresses an action, an occurrence, or a state of being. It is the engine of the sentence.\n• **Types**: Action verbs (physical/mental actions like *run*, *think*) and Linking/Helping verbs (state of being or helper verbs like *is*, *are*, *have*).\n• **Examples**:\n  - The student *writes* clean code. (Action verb showing physical activity)\n  - Bujji *is* a helpful companion. (Linking verb showing state of being)\n  - They *have* *completed* the quiz. (*have* is a helping verb; *completed* is the main action verb)\n\n### 4. Adjective (Noun Modifier)\nAn adjective describes or modifies a noun or pronoun, giving it color, detail, or specificity.\n• **Examples**:\n  - The *clever* student solved the *difficult* problem. (*clever* describes the student; *difficult* describes the problem)\n  - Bujji has *neon* eyes and a *sleek* design. (*neon* and *sleek* describe the eyes and design)\n\n### 5. Adverb (Action or Description Modifier)\nAn adverb modifies a verb, an adjective, or another adverb. It usually answers how, when, where, or to what extent, and often ends in -ly.\n• **Examples**:\n  - She spoke *clearly* during the presentation. (*clearly* modifies the verb *spoke*, describing how she spoke)\n  - The robot is *extremely* smart. (*extremely* modifies the adjective *smart*, describing how smart)\n  - They ran *very* fast. (*very* modifies the adverb *fast*, describing how fast)\n\n### 6. Preposition (Position and Time Connector)\nA preposition shows spatial, temporal, or logical relationship between a noun (or pronoun) and other words.\n• **Examples**:\n  - The book is *on* the desk. (*on* shows the spatial position of the book relative to the desk)\n  - We will meet *after* class. (*after* shows the relationship in time)\n  - The path led *through* the forest. (*through* shows the direction of movement)\n\n### 7. Conjunction (Connector Word)\nA conjunction connects words, phrases, or entire clauses together.\n• **Types**: Coordinating (like *and*, *but*, *so*) and Subordinating (like *because*, *although*, *if*).\n• **Examples**:\n  - She wanted to study, *but* she was tired. (*but* joins two independent ideas)\n  - Bujji *and* Clara completed the project *because* they worked together. (*and* joins two nouns; *because* joins the main clause with the reason)\n\n### 8. Interjection (Expressive Word)\nAn interjection is a word or phrase that expresses sudden, strong emotion. It stands grammatically independent from the rest of the sentence.\n• **Examples**:\n  - *Wow!* That was an amazing explanation. (*Wow!* expresses excitement or wonder)\n  - *Oops!* I deleted the incorrect file. (*Oops!* expresses minor distress or accidental mistake)"
    },
    {
        "id": "lesson_2",
        "title": "Tenses: Present, Past & Future",
        "intro": "How to anchor actions correctly in time.",
        "content": "Tenses indicate when an action happens. There are three main times with four aspects each:\n\n### Present Tense\n* **Simple Present**: Daily routines or facts. *'She walks to school.'*\n* **Present Continuous**: Action happening right now. *'She is walking to school.'*\n* **Present Perfect**: Action completed in past but relevant now. *'She has walked to school.'*\n\n### Past Tense\n* **Simple Past**: Finished past action. *'He completed the assignment.'*\n* **Past Continuous**: Ongoing action in the past. *'He was writing an email when the bell rang.'*\n* **Past Perfect**: Action finished before another past action. *'He had completed it before leaving.'*\n\n### Future Tense\n* **Simple Future**: Upcoming actions. *'We will study tomorrow.'*"
    },
    {
        "id": "lesson_3",
        "title": "Subject-Verb Agreement",
        "intro": "Singular subjects need singular verbs; plural subjects need plural verbs.",
        "content": "Subject-verb agreement is the foundational rule of syntax.\n\n### Golden Rules:\n* **Singular subject = Singular verb**:\n  * *'The student works hard.'* (Subject: student, Verb: works)\n* **Plural subject = Plural verb**:\n  * *'The students work hard.'* (Subject: students, Verb: work)\n\n### Common Pitfalls:\n* **Words like 'each', 'either', 'neither', 'everyone' are singular**:\n  * *'Each of the students has a book.'* (Correct)\n  * *'Neither of the systems is offline.'* (Correct)\n* **Intervening phrases** (like *as well as*, *along with*) do not change the number of the subject:\n  * *'Bujji, along with his companions, is helping.'* (Subject is Bujji, which is singular)."
    },
    {
        "id": "lesson_4",
        "title": "Prepositions and Conjunctions",
        "intro": "Connecting ideas and locating them in space and time.",
        "content": "Prepositions and conjunctions act as the glue of your sentences.\n\n### Prepositions\nPrepositions tell us where or when something is in relation to something else:\n* **In**: Used for enclosed spaces, months, years. *'In the room'*, *'In June'*.\n* **On**: Used for surfaces, days, dates. *'On the table'*, *'On Monday'*.\n* **At**: Used for specific locations, points of time. *'At 5:00 PM'*, *'At the entrance'*.\n\n### Conjunctions\nConjunctions connect words, phrases, or clauses:\n* **Coordinating Conjunctions (FANBOYS)**: For, And, Nor, But, Or, Yet, So.\n* **Subordinating Conjunctions**: Because, although, since, until, while. They establish dependency.\n  * *'Although she was tired, she completed the quiz.'*"
    },
    {
        "id": "lesson_5",
        "title": "Active vs. Passive Voice",
        "intro": "Direct action versus formal reporting style.",
        "content": "Voice describes the relationship between the action and the subject.\n\n### Active Voice\nThe subject performs the action. It is direct, clear, and concise:\n* *'The student submitted the quiz.'* (Subject: student, Action: submitted)\n\n### Passive Voice\nThe subject receives the action. Used when the doer is unknown, obvious, or in formal/scientific reporting:\n* *'The quiz was submitted by the student.'*\n* *'The server logs were updated.'* (Focus is on logs, doer is secondary)\n\n### Professional Tip:\nIn emails or professional requests, prefer the **Active Voice** to sound polite and direct: *'Please review the draft'* is better than *'The draft should be reviewed by you.'*"
    }
]

